00:18:07.200 --> 00:18:09.950
&gt;&gt;Tavis Smiley: Yeah, I think this piece is
called "I had everything."

00:18:09.950 --> 00:18:17.500
And the short answer is that last summer Dr.
West and I took a poverty tour.

00:18:17.500 --> 00:18:22.290
We got on a bus and went to 11 states and
18 cities across the country.

00:18:22.290 --> 00:18:27.960
Trying to get a sense of what poverty had
really done to America.

00:18:27.960 --> 00:18:32.900
What was the impact of the so-called "great
recession" on everyday people in this country?

00:18:32.900 --> 00:18:38.200
Doc and I believe that poverty is the moral
and the spiritual issue of our time.

00:18:38.200 --> 00:18:39.740
But it required us to do a little more research.

00:18:39.740 --> 00:18:42.400
We wanted to get out on the road.

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:47.220
Give up a part of our summer, to try to see
what the new face of poverty looked like.

00:18:47.220 --> 00:18:50.310
So for so long in this country, poverty has
been color coded.

00:18:50.310 --> 00:18:52.020
So you think poverty, you think black.

00:18:52.020 --> 00:18:54.610
You think poverty, you think brown.

00:18:54.610 --> 00:18:58.580
But with the Census Bureau letting us know
that one out of every two Americans is either

00:18:58.580 --> 00:19:01.440
in or near poverty, 50 percent of our nation.

00:19:01.440 --> 00:19:04.310
150 million people are either in or near poverty.

00:19:04.310 --> 00:19:08.870
Clearly the face of poverty had changed and
we wanted to see what the new face of poverty

00:19:08.870 --> 00:19:14.120
looked like, to have a better understanding
of how we are to advance our work, Stacy,

00:19:14.120 --> 00:19:18.500
about what poverty is, what it is not, how
to reduce it.

00:19:18.500 --> 00:19:19.500
How to eradicate it.

00:19:19.500 --> 00:19:20.630
So we got on this bus.

00:19:20.630 --> 00:19:22.550
Again, 11 states, 18 cities.

00:19:22.550 --> 00:19:25.280
Had a documentary crew in tow with me.

00:19:25.280 --> 00:19:30.250
And we turned that tour into a week long special
on PBS.

00:19:30.250 --> 00:19:36.130
So for five nights on national television,
on PBS, there were these short pieces.

00:19:36.130 --> 00:19:39.500
These seven to ten minute pieces.

00:19:39.500 --> 00:19:44.280
On each night about what we saw, about a particular
theme, particular subject matter, particular

00:19:44.280 --> 00:19:46.130
aspect or angle of poverty.

00:19:46.130 --> 00:19:49.340
And that these short mini-docs, if you will.

00:19:49.340 --> 00:19:54.450
These mini-docs were then followed by extensive
conversation with experts about these particular

00:19:54.450 --> 00:19:55.450
issues.

00:19:55.450 --> 00:19:59.200
So this is a piece that aired on one of the
five nights of the PBS special.

00:19:59.200 --> 00:20:01.300
Born of our poverty tour last summer.

00:20:01.300 --> 00:20:03.730
The precursor for the book we're gonna talk
about today.

00:20:03.730 --> 00:20:05.040
It's about seven to eight minutes.

00:20:05.040 --> 00:20:08.120
It's called "I had everything" and I think
it'll give you a good sense of what we experienced

00:20:08.120 --> 00:20:09.120
on the tour.

00:20:09.120 --> 00:20:10.120
So.

00:20:10.120 --> 00:20:11.120
Take a look.

